name: "Chinese" Garage
description: A Grade II listed motor garage and petrol station built in the style of a Japanese pagoda in 1928. Now a Tesco Express.
address: Chinese Garage, Stone Park Avenue, BR3 3FE

name: 'Maiden Voyage' by JeeYoung Lee
description: For NOW Gallery‚Äôs 2022 Art Commission JeeYoung Lee has created an environment inspired by memories, dreams, emotions, and her personal experience. The artist reinterprets her psychological landscape and thoughts into this environment.

name: 1 Finsbury Avenue
description: 1 Finsbury Avenue is a Grade II listed building constructed in the early 1980s by Arup Associates (Peter Foggo). As the first building in the Broadgate development it was significant in defining the speculative office typology in London.

name: 1 Halliwick Road
description: A low energy refurbishment of an Edwardian house, with rear extension and loft conversion. Wood fibre insulation, MVHR, airtightness layer, triple glazing, timber structure and low embodied energy materials.

name: 15 and a half Consort Road
description: As per Grand Designs, the opening roof, the retracting loo and sliding bed-bath typify this extraordinary response to constraints of a tight budget on a brownfield site. Shortlisted RIBA Awards 2006. One of nation's favourite TV houses.
address: 15 and a half Consort Road, SE15 2PH

name: 17 Chesterford Gardens
description: Refurbishment of a first floor flat in a detached Victorian house in Hampstead, set within a conservation area, undertaken to create a bespoke contemporary minimalist family home for furniture designers.

name: 17a‚Äì79b Mansfield Road (access to two flats)
description: The long terrace at 17a‚Äì79b Mansfield Road was the last part of the post-war Gospel Oak Redevelopment Area to be completed, and formed part of the London Borough of Camden‚Äôs ‚ÄòGolden Era‚Äô of housing under borough architect Sydney Cook.

name: 186A Uxbridge Road
description:
Semi-detached residential 2-bed house totally refurbished by the owner-architect.
The main works included demolition of str. walls to achieve open plan living, new bathrooms, kitchen, porch, windows, green roof, UFH and insulation.

name: 23 Sedgeford Road
description: Completely carbon neutral terraced house following a retrofit solar, batteries and air source heat pump installation. Existing radiators, double glazing and roof / loft insulation.

name: 264 Westbourne Park Road
description: New building as an urban accent - two independent houses atop each other. Contemporary in design it draws from the tectonic composition of adjacent Victorian houses. Features include rain water harvesting,  roof garden, solar water heating.

name: 3D Printing at Design District
description: We are opening the doors of our 3D Printing Studio at the Design District for all to experience the wonders of 3D printing. Come learn about this innovative technology, touch the materials, and see 3D printers in action!
address: 10 Monro Way, Unit 1.1, Building A4, Greenwich

name: 40 Clarence Mews
description:
Home & Studio for Family, Architecture & Movement, part of the
hidden creative side of Clarence Mews. Includes An exhibition of the 'Purbeckian Masque' from Arts University Bournemouth M.Arch students

name: 9-10 Stock Orchard Street
description: The project is a house and studio using innovative technologies based around principles of sustainable design. Materials were chosen to limit environmental impact and produce innovative spatial and formal solutions to urban live/work.

name: A House for Artists
description: A House for Artists is an ambitious project, designed to provide affordable, sustainable housing for artists, who will offer long-term civic and cultural engagement for communities in Barking Town Centre. Drop in to the creative workshop.

name: Altab Ali Park
description: Altab Ali Park was renamed in 1998 after a murdered 25-year-old Bangladeshi Sylheti clothing worker. Formerly known as St. Mary's Park, it is the site of the old 14 C white church, St. Mary Matfelon which gave Whitechapel its name.

name: Anderson WW2 Bomb Shelter
description:
Original Anderson Shelter, set in concrete and covered in earth.
The shelter is in the back garden of a four storey 1850s terraced house. Access to the house is down five steps.  Access to the shelter is down four deep steps.

name: Argentine Ambassador's Residence
description:
"ARGENTINA AT THE LONDON DESIGN FESTIVAL 2022" 
During Open House Festival people will have the unique opportunity to visit and explore the historic mansion host to the exhibition ‚ÄúCreative experience- From Argentina to the world‚Äù

name: Art in Perpetuity Trust
description: Open Studios, provides a unique glimpse to the architectural spaces and working studios of APT artists.  Over the weekend, there is also the opportunity to see our Group Show in the Gallery, curated by and featuring APT artist's work.

name: B2
description: A pair of un-identical twin buildings that slope steeply on one side to open views through Design District London. The buildings provide light industrial spaces on three levels with workshops and retail at ground floor.
address: B2, Design District, 12 Soames Walk, SE10 0AX

name: Black Stone House
description: The concrete framed structure of this apartment building adjusts to its irregularly shaped corner plot. Exposed beams and columns support lime-washed interiors and a scratched stucco fa√ßade forms an abstract expression to the street.

name: Blackheath Quaker Meeting House
description: Small 1970s concrete building with a raised lantern. Designed to fit in with older buildings in the conservation area , and make the most of the split-level site. Architect Trevor Dannatt. Grade ll Listed.

name: Blenheim Gardens Estate
description: Blenheim Gardens Estate was designed and built in the late 1960s - early 1970s by Lambeth‚Äôs Architecture Department under Ted Hollamby. It marks the shift from system-built high-rise towards communal and pedestrian-dominated spaces.

name: Bow Church ‚Äì St Mary
description: Medieval village church, restored 1899 and again in 1952 after WWII bomb damage. 15C font and memorials from five centuries. Grade II* listed. Refurbished for 700th anniversary in 2011; bell tower and cupola restored in 2017-18.

name: Bruce Castle Museum
description: Tudor Manor House built for Sir William Compton in 1514, substantially altered in 17C, 18C & 19C. A museum since 1906 housing local history and community collections, archives, art & exhibitions of Bruce Castle, and Haringey area.
address: Bruce Castle Museum,, Lordship Lane, Tottenham

name: Build your own model tree house at Elephant Park
description:
A free, informal workshop session led by members of Bell Phillips Architects for children to build their own model lantern, inspired by The Tree House, and learn about architecture. 

Drop in any time between 3-5pm.
address: The Tree House, Elephant Park, SE17 1HL

name: Burlington House: Linnean Society of London
description: The world's oldest active biological society. Founded in 1788, the Society takes its name from the Swedish naturalist Carl Linnaeus whose botanical, zoological and library collections have been in its keeping since 1829.

name: Burlington House: Royal Astronomical Society
description: The home of the Royal Astronomical Society since 1874, refurbished in 2007. Part of the extension to Burlington House to provide accommodation for learned societies.

name: C3 - Bureau
description: C3 is home to Bureau, a members club at the heart of Design District. Its undulating white facade creates informal pockets of space on the interior, ideal for flexible working models.

name: Caledonian Park: Clock Tower Tours
description: Opened in 1855 as centrepiece of the Metropolitan Cattle Market. The clock tower offers magnificent views over London. The clock mechanism was made by John Moore of Clerkenwell. The tower has been renovated with help from the Heritage Fund.
address: Cally Clock Tower Centre, Market Road, N7 9HF

name: Canal club community centre reopening party
description:
Learn about architect Julian Sofaer and join in with activities related to our community garden.

Draw local endangered flowers: 
Sunday 3pm - 4pm

Learn about fruit & veg grown locally: 
Saturday 2.30pm - 4pm 
Sunday 1pm - 2.30pm
address: Canal club community centre, Waterloo gardens

name: Cannizaro Studios
description:
Victorian Potting sheds converted to artists' studios set within the grounds of Grade II listed Cannizaro Park.
The eight resident artists will be displaying their work during the festival at these unique studios.
address: The old Potting sheds, Cannizaro Park, SW19 4UW

name: Christ Church, Streatham
description: Grade I listed pioneering brick polychromy. Designed with early Christian, Italian, Ottoman, Alhambran, Mamluk, Sevillean and Ancient Egyptian influences with fine mosaics and stained glass by Crane, Bentley. Lee and Hayward.

name: Company Drinks/Barking Park Outdoor Bowls Pavilion
description: The former sports pavilion and its large outdoor are used as a community hub by Company Drinks. The multifunctional building and garden have recently been upgraded alongside a stakeholder-led physical and cultural access concept and design.
address: Company Drinks Pavilion, Outdoor Bowls Pavilion

name: Conway Hall
description: The home of Conway Hall Ethical Society, an organisation renowned as a hub for free speech and progressive thought. Grade II listed building with both Arts and Crafts and Art Deco features adding to its distinctive style.

name: Copper Maisonette
description:
A reconfiguration and additional floor to a purpose built maisonette in South West London. 

The interior space and circulation are opened up with Oak detailing throughout. Externally a Copper roof drapes over the new structure.

name: Courtyard House
description: Courtyard House is a minimalist Victorian conversion featuring a serene Japanese-inspired courtyard. The house has been meticulously redesigned to offer a unique spatial experience, with a generous bright layout and handcrafted materiality.

name: Cromwell Place
description: A first of its kind global arts destination, Cromwell Place is located in five Grade II Listed townhouses in South Kensington. Home to some of the world‚Äôs most exciting rotating art exhibitors with a range in specialties.

name: Crystal Palace Bowl
description: Crystal Palace Bowl is a South London icon: A venue of legends from Pink Floyd to Bob Marley, with a Stirling Prize nominated sculptural stage, revived from ruin by a local community campaign and ready to host the next generation of talent!

name: Cut Glass Studio Ltd, Tottenham Hale
description: Unit used as an art studio in a small industrial estate.
address: 15-16 The High Cross Centre, Fountayne Road

name: Dalston C.L.R. James Library & Hackney Archives
description: 4-storey multi-purpose, state of the art library and archives building.

name: Dalston Eastern Curve Garden
description: A vital community garden offering a model for maximum good for communities and for the environment on a small urban plot. It is now a site of Local Importance for Nature Conservation. Shortlisted for the Open City Stewardship Awards 2021.

name: Dorich House Museum
description: The former studio home of the sculptor Dora Gordine and her husband the Hon. Richard Hare, a scholar of Russian art and literature. 1930s house over four floors including a flat roof terrace and views of Richmond Park.
address: Dorich House Museum, 67 Kingston Vale, SW15 3RN

name: Douglas Fir House
description: A low-energy, prefabricated Canadian Douglas fir rear extension to the garden flat of a converted Edwardian terraced house.

name: Ealing Abbey Church of St Benedict
description: Begun in 1897 and a century later is almost completed. Architects include F and E Walters (1897, the nave), Stanley Kerr Bates (1960, transepts), and Sir William Whitfield (1997, choir and apse).

name: Ethelburga Tower, Battersea
description: Ethelburga Tower is a 17-storey block of flats near Battersea Park.  The building was designed by the LCC  Architects Dept with Ove Arup & Partners as consulting engineers.  It was built by Tersons of Finchley and completed in 1966.

name: Exploring Spring Grove Isleworth
description: Centred on Spring Grove House, once Sir Joseph Banks home the 1850s vision was for John Taylor Jnr designed grand villas.  Today's  wider architecture includes a former college by John Norton & P Massey plus quirky arts & crafts properties.

name: Former Grosvenor Cinema, now Zoroastrian Centre For Europe
description: Grade II* listed Art Deco building with well-preserved interior. Auditorium with deep coved ribs; proscenium arch flanked by fluted columns. Restoration fully funded by  donations from Zoroastrian faith community, without government grants.

name: GARDEN OF EARTHLY DELIGHTSüå±üêùüçÖü¶ã
description: The Garden of Earthly Delights is a community garden and a "meanwhile" space to raise awareness of empty spaces in the city, grow food for the local community and increase biodiversity. We hold workshops and events to which all are welcome.

name: Greenside Primary School
description: One of only 2 schools designed using Ern≈ë Goldfinger's school building system - precast reinforced concrete frame with brick infill. Mural of school subjects by Gordon Cullen. Grade II* listed. Bouncing Off the Wall C20th Arts Fair 12-5

name: Gubns @ Bloqs: Tour, Workshop, Party
description: London‚Äôs biggest open-access workshop, Bloqs, partners with the platform for architect-makers, Gubns, to host a series of tours, a metal workshop, and a party to celebrate all makers: https://www.eventbrite.com/cc/gubns-bloqs-1113879

name: Hackney Empire
description: Hackney Empire is a grade II* listed building. The theatre was built as a music hall in 1901, designed by the architect Frank Matcham. It is now an exceptional variety theatre for the 21st century, serving the local community and beyond.

name: Holy Trinity Church Sloane Square
description: A sumptuous feast of Victorian stained glass & bold sacred sculpture in what Sir John Betjeman called the 'cathedral of the Arts and Crafts movement.' Work by William Morris, Edward Burne-Jones, William Blake Richamind & Christopher Whall.

name: Homework Open Studio (A4)
description: Visit our studio in David Kohn Architects' building A4 in Design District and see where we formulate and manufacture all of our products. Sample our full range and take part in a perfume oil making workshop.

name: Ingrebourne Valley Visitor Centre
description: Ingrebourne Valley Visitor Centre, at Hornchurch Country Park, the Former RAF Hornchurch Airfield.

name: Institut fran√ßais du Royaume-Uni
description: 1939 Art Deco Grade II listed building refurbished in 1950, then restructured and modernised in 2014. Contains an authentically classic cinema, private salons and multimedia library.

name: International Presbyterian Church
description:
IPC, Ealing opened their winning extended building in 2018, designed by Piercy architects. 
The original 1912 chapel designed by John Ninian Comper and  is a grade 2 listed building is still intact and was integrated into the new design

name: Jonathan Tuckey Design Studio
description: This transformation of a derelict pub into an architecture studio doubles up as a gallery and lecture theatre. The new office is an example of the practice‚Äôs approach towards existing structures and intelligent architectural interventions.

name: Kaymet Factory
description: The operational factory of Kaymet, a maker of trays and trolleys since 1947. A hidden 1950s building with a small yard, originally a printing works. It is brick built, with clear-storey glazing and tubular truss north-light main shed roof.

name: Kingston Guildhall and History Centre
description: Built in the Georgian style, the Guildhall brought together Kingston's administrative functions. Purpose-built Magistrates Courts were included in the building, part of which are now home to Kingston History Centre.
address: High Street , Kingston upon Thames, KT1 1EU

name: Levitt Bernstein's Studio
description:
A modern, low energy and highly flexible studio for architects, landscape architects and urban designers within a former industrial
building.

name: LivingFunky House
description: Wates Built 1960s Semi, extended & renovated into a vibrant, colourful stylish 21st Century home. Embracing Midcentury & Modern design with Bold Colours, Patterns & Materials to create the feeling of space, light & individuality throughout.

name: London Metropolitan Archives
description: LMA's older building was built in the late 1930s for the Temple Press and has many original features.   Purpose built extension in early 1990s for archival storage. Public rooms remodelled by Bisset Adams in 2000s.

name: London Screen Academy
description: The London Screen Academy is a unique learning environment in a heritage building transformed from a disused radio and television factory into a world class specialist sixth form education facility.

name: Markfield Beam Engine and House
description:
A masterpiece of Victorian engineering, Markfield Beam Engine provided a vital public health facility from 1855-1964. 

On 17 & 18 Sept the 1888 beam engine will be steaming as follows:
12.30 - 1.15pm 
2.00 - 2.45pm 
3.30 - 4.15pm
address: Markfield Park, Markfield Road, South Tottenham

name: Migration Museum
description: The Migration Museum is located inside the Lewisham Shopping Centre.

name: Millennium Mills: Feeding Edwardian London
description: We will show how the long-distance trade with Canada  helped feed London‚Äôs growing population of 7 million people by 1910.  Our "museum without walls" will use virtual reality technology to to visualise historical connections.
address: Western Gateway, Royal Victoria Dock, E16 1FA

name: Mount Pleasant
description: A former Victorian workhouse that has been transformed through LB Camden's Community Investment Programme into a state of the art facility for 50 homeless people laid out around a beautiful suntrap courtyard.

name: Mountain View House
description: A radical transformation of an Edwardian Semi that has been completely opened up and renovated with bold materials and bright colours. A stage-set mountain is elevated on an exposed structure to form the striking rear extension.

name: Museum of London Docklands
description: Grade I listed, late Georgian sugar warehouse now housing the Museum of London Docklands. Sensitively restored, the new multimedia displays coexist with the massive timber and brick structures of the original building.

name: Museum of Neoliberalism
description: The museum is situated in a shopfront in Leegate Shopping Centre, which has been described by the Evening Standard as "the worst shopping precinct in the country."

name: Museum of the Order of St John
description: St John's Gate in Clerkenwell dates from 1504 and was built for the Knights Hospitaller. 19th and early 20th century additions by Richard Norman Shaw and John Oldrid Scott. Grade I listed. Home to the Museum of the Order of St John.
address: St John's Gate, St John's Lane, Clerkenwell

name: New Ground (online only)
description: 25 homes designed with the Older Women‚Äôs Co-Housing group using PTE‚Äôs ‚Äòfabric first‚Äô approach which maximises the benefits of orientation, air-tightness, insulation and following the co-housing model. www.youtube.com/watch?v=9q25nbEl8rg

name: New London Architecture
description: Visit New London Architecture's pop-up gallery at Westfield Stratford City to see the largest model of London. Celebrate the 10-year anniversary of the Games and learn more about the past and future of Queen Elizabeth Olympic Park.
address: The Street , Westfield Stratford City , E20 1EN

name: Nunhead Cemetery
description: Magnificent Victorian cemetery with Gothic chapel & restored & ruined lodge. One of London's wildest cemeteries. Part restored with the help of a lottery grant. 52 acres of woodland, with bats, owls, foxes & squirrels. Grade II*  landscape.

name: Old Kent Road Arts Club
description: Old Kent Road Arts Club is a community project space that lives inside an old sofa shop on Old Kent Road. Come and see how we've transformed this vacant retail space into a thriving creative hub that offers free activities for all ages.

name: Old Royal Naval College
description: Sir Christopher Wren's riverside masterpiece in Greenwich, built as the Royal Hospital for Seamen and begun in 1696.
address: Old Royal Naval College, Greenwich, SE10 9NN

name: OmVed Gardens Chelsea Flower Show Pavilion
description: A pavilion inspired by the organic shapes of nature and the transformational potential of seeds, currently hosting the exhibition "Saving Seed". The walls can rotate position allowing the space to perform like a seed cracking open.

name: Open Bookshop at 1 Finsbury Avenue
description: Celebrate the best writing about architects and the city at AHMM‚Äôs pop-up bookshop at Morag Myerscough‚Äôs Atoll. We‚Äôve curated a special collection of books and maps by established publishers, smaller independents and Open City itself.

name: People's Museum Somers Town
description:
A great little museum set in the Grade 2 listed Ossulston Estate - a prime example of pre-war Social housing - based on Karl Marz Hof in Vienna.
Open Wednesdays to Saturdays throughout Festival 
Sunday 11th Event

name: Poets Corner
description: A small glass extension unlocks a compact Victorian terrace around a sunken kitchen, connecting upper and lower ground levels with a dramatic double height space.

name: Pushkin House
description: The independent cultural centre Pushkin House will contribute to this year's Open House Festival through a programme of events and community initiatives at its Grade-II listed building in Bloomsbury Square.

name: Quentin Blake Centre for Illustration - New River Head
description:
An industrial heritage site that was the hub of one of London‚Äôs first major pieces of urban infrastructure.
Its 18th and 19th century buildings will be restored by Tim Ronalds Architects to create the Quentin Blake Centre for Illustration.

name: Reimagining Orchard Gardens Community Centre
description: Kin Structures¬†and residents of Orchard Gardens estate have been making art to explore new futures for the local community centre. Join this final event to participate in their journey of reimagining community centres for the 21st century.
address: Orchard Gardens Community Centre, Columbine Way

name: Roca London Gallery
description: Designed by the world renowned Zaha Hadid Architects, Roca London Gallery is a unique space where water acts as the architectural theme. Guests can also visit 'Everything Flows', a major exhibition exploring the work of Zaha Hadid Design.

name: SUNDAY OPENING CANCELLED  Oswyth Road
description: The project‚Äôs aim was to extend the ground floor to provide more space for the dining area and refurbish the rest of the floor to create a coherent whole from the entrance to the garden.

name: SUNDAY OPENING CANCELLED Peckham Courtyard
description: Peckham Courtyard is a refurbishment and extension of a Victorian, end of terrace house in Peckham, London. The clients wanted to create a better connection to the sky and garden.

name: Small Beer Brewery
description: The Small Beer Brewery was founded in 2017 by James Grundy and  Felix James. It is the first of its kind, specialising in brewing world class beer at a sociable strength.

name: St Andrew's Kingsbury (new church)
description: Meticulous 1930s rebuilding (complete with original furnishings) of an 1840s Marylebone church. Grade I listed. Contains works by Pugin, Burges, Street, Pearson and Butterfield.
address: junction of Church Lane/Tudor Gardens/ Old Chur

name: St Augustine's Tower
description: Grade I listed, remaining tower of medieval parish church, with working late 16C clock. New exhibition of Hackney's history. Extensive views from roof. (Organised by Hackney Historic Buildings Trust).

name: St Barnabas' Church and Mission Hall
description: Early 20th C Grade II* listed church designed by CH Reilly. Byzantine in structure but prefiguring Modernism in its aesthetic, Nairn judged it ‚Äúthe best church of its date in London‚Äù, Reilly ‚Äúthe building I should like to be remembered by‚Äù.
address: St Barnabas' Church, Shackewell Row, E8 2EA

name: St Jude on the Hill
description: Eccentric Edwardian church, Grade I listed. Described by Simon Jenkins as 'one of Lutyens' most distinctive creations'. Extensive 20C wall-paintings by Walter Starmer, memorial to horses of WWI. Local archives display.

name: St Lawrence Church, Morden
description: Grade I listed Norman brick-built church consisting of a nave and chancel. Tower at the west end. Gothic-style stone windows from the old church inserted into the present 1636 structure. Rare 17th Century glass was restored in 2020.

name: St Margaret's Church, Lee
description:
The Church was built in 1839/41 as a white 'Hall-Church'. 
The 1870s Gothic Revivalism was overseen to a very high standard, by James Brooks and helped by 10 top craftsmen of the day. We also have a WWI Memorial by Violet Pinwill.
address: St Margarets Church,  Lee Terrace, SE13 5DN

name: St Mary Magdalene Church
description: Fine Victorian Gothic church with impressive windows and painted chancel. Paintings by Buckeridge and Westlake 1897. Restoration of chancel paintings was to celebrate the Diamond Jubilee of Queen Elizabeth II. (2012)

name: St Mary the Virgin
description: Small Grade I listed 12C chapel in lovely churchyard setting, it retains original architectural features and has interesting brasses, monuments and stained glass windows.
address: Church Road, Manor Park, Little Ilford, E12 6HA

name: St Mary's Church Bromley
description:
A plain Victorian Church set in a wooded Churchyard, with a vibrant and striking set of Murals around the altar and the Choir. 
Has indoor toilet facilities. 
A good quality well used organ in good condition, and an excellent accoustic
address: St Mary's Church, College Road, Bromley

name: St Mary's Church, Battersea
description: Classic Grade I listed Georgian church with outstanding interior and monuments. Renovated 2019/20.

name: St Matthew's Church
description:
St Matthews is Grade II listed, built 1883-4 and designed by the architect Alfred Jowers. 
It features a WW1 memorial screen designed by Reginald Hallward and stained glass some believed to be by Edward Frampton
address: St Matthews church, North Common Road, W5 2QA

name: St Michael and All Angels Church
description: James Maltby Bignall (1827-1885) worked in the practice of Sir George Gilbert Scott, the architect of St Pancras Station. The style of St Michael's is late Gothic Revival, in its size and height reminiscent of Northern European churches.

name: St Nicholas Church, Chislehurst
description: Medieval Parish Church, 15C, enlarged & rebuilt in 19C. Shingle spire 1857, by Wollaston. Chancel by Ferrey, lengthened with East wall by Bodley & Garner. Scadbury Chapel (Walsingham tombs), with rood screen. Clock by Dent, 1858.

name: St Pancras Chambers and Clock Tower
description: Former Midland Grand Hotel, now St Pancras Renaissance Hotel and Chambers apartments. Includes hotel lobby and clock tower.
address: The Forecourt, St Pancras Station, Euston Road

name: St Pancras Church & Crypt
description: The church (1822 - Grade I listed) is an early and important example of Greek Revival architecture in London. Significant features include the caryatids and tower copied from the Acropolis and the atmospheric crypt.
address: Euston Road/Upper Woburn Place NW1, NW1 2BA

name: St Patrick's Church
description: Built thanks to a generous gift from local benefactress, Mrs Lavinia Keene, St Patrick's was consecrated in July 1940 and is unusual in style. The concrete and brick interior contrasts with the dramatic, colourful reredos. Grade II listed.

name: St Stephen's Church, Dulwich
description: Designed by Charles Barry Jr in the Victorian Gothic style, it has been a landmark in Dulwich since it was painted by the French Impressionist Camille Pissarro in 1870. There is a fine fresco painted by Sir Edward Poynter in the chancel.
address: St Stephen's Church, College Road, Dulwich

name: Stanley Arts
description: A public hall, theatre and gallery in grand Edwardian style. Grade II listed, Stanley made fun of the Victorian style with grand ornamentation. It reflects Stanley's interest in science, the arts and public cultural improvement.

name: Streatham Space Project - Photography Exhibition: The Fighting Spirit of South London
description: A neighborhood theatre, music and arts venue using cultural events to bring people together. We pride ourselves on being a welcoming space celebrating everyone's creativity from children to emerging producers to experienced artists.

name: Studio 11G Weber Industries
description: This former factory was refurbished in 2011 by SPACE to provide studios for artists and creative makers. Weber Industries, a bespoke fabrication and custom design studio, has operated in the street-facing ground floor studios since 2012.

name: Suleymaniye Mosque
description: 6-storey building featuring a Western exterior and traditional Islamic interior, modelled on the Blue Mosque in Istanbul. Has dome and minaret tower.

name: Taylor & Chatto Courts and Wilmott Court, Frampton Park Estate
description: Taylor Court and Chatto Court, together with Wilmott Court, form a pair of award-winning mixed-tenure housing, accommodating 45 new homes and commissioned by the Hackney Council on two sites at the edge of the post-war Frampton Park Estate.

name: The Boleyn Tavern
description: The Boleyn is a prominent landmark at a crossroads right by the former West Ham football ground. It is an exuberant piece of French-style Renaissance architecture built in 1899-1900 and reopened in June 2021 after a spectacular restoration.
address: 1 Barking Road, The Boleyn Tavern, E6 1PW

name: The Church of Our Most Holy Redeemer
description: A unique II* listed Italianate church by John Dando Sedding with attached Campanile and Institute Building. Of particular significance in the church is the imposing baldacchino over the High Altar, which dominates the east end.

name: The City Churches: St. Michael Cornhill
description: A church building has occupied this sight for at least a thousand years.  Destroyed in the Great Fire of 1666, but rebuilt in the 1670s. Known as a Wren church, the architect was Nicholas Young.
address: St. Michael's Cornhill, St. Michael's Alley

name: The Experimental Weave Lab
description: The Experimental Weave Lab is the City of London‚Äôs first contemporary weaving studio. For Open House London we are throwing open the doors to our studio for a work in progress exhibition and live weaving.
address: St Olave Parish Hall, Mark Lane, EC3R 7LQ

name: The Family Kitchen, Royal Botanic Gardens Kew
description: The Family Kitchen & Shop, Royal Botanic Gardens Kew, designed by architects HOK with front of house interiors by Mizzi Studio and Lumsden Design, is an environmentally driven, education-led food space for visitors of all ages.
address: Royal Botanic Gardens,   , Kew Rd, TW9 3AB

name: The Foundry
description: Tucked behind a busy road in W12, this former foundry is a multi-level development featuring an architects‚Äô studio with courtyards and spaces for exhibitions and musical performances. The  building's 15m brick chimney is a local landmark.

name: The Mildmay Club
description: A rare example of a large purpose built metropolitan working men‚Äôs club with over 100 years of history. A once dignified building, revival Queen Anne style in the late-Victorian period, Grade II listed in 2019.

name: The Post Building
description:
London is known for its rooftops. The Roof Garden at The Post Building has been designed as a one-off location for enjoyment, work and wellness looking out over some of its most memorable.

Open to the public 7 days a week!

name: The Priory, Orpington
description: Grade II listed building dating back to 1270. Following the dissolution of Christ Church Priory in Orpington in the 1530s, the house became a rectory. Additions were built in 1959 to put in a library.

name: The Serpentine Coffee House, The Royal Parks, Opposite The Serpentine Gallery
description:
The Serpentine Coffee House overlooking the Serpentine Lake designed by Mizzi Studio, with its undulating brass canopy roof that echoes a stingray‚Äôs flight through water,  has added a
new architectural landmark to London‚Äôs Hyde Park.
address: The Serpentine Coffee House, W Carriage Drive

name: The Swedenborg Society
description: Grade II-listed Georgian domestic building c.1760, formerly part of Bedford Estate. Interior refurbished 1924-5 to form lecture hall (restored 2014), library, bookshop and offices. Oak woodwork and green Doulton tiles line the staircase.

name: The Tin Tabernacle / Cambridge Hall
description:
Built 1863 - a large corrugated iron chapel. Inside was transformed after the last war into a battleship by local sailors for Sea Cadets. 
It has decks, portholes a Bofors Gun and alter from the set of the 1964 film Becket.

name: The Wash Houses (Formerly The Womens Library)
description: RIBA award-winning building.  Part listed frontage with purpose built archive and exhibition building added to the rear in 2002. The building now houses the University's Special Collections & Archives

name: Thornhill Square
description: A tour of one of the largest and best preserved early Victorian squares and gardens in London, also with a magnificent and original public library of 1906, which shows Byzantine and Art Nouveau influences, and a remarkable Gothic church.
address: Meet outside the main door of St Andrew‚Äôs Churc

name: Tooting Bec Lido
description: Outdoor pool 100x33 yards. One million gallons of unheated water. Iconic outdoor cubicle doors, fountain and caf√© added in the 1930s, with Art Deco style entrance in 2001. Sports hall pavilion added in 2016.
address: Tooting Bec Lido, Tooting Bec Road, SW16 1RU

name: Turning Earth Ceramics Haringey - N22
description: The new ceramics studio occupies the top floor of a beautiful old saw-toothed factory building within the Crawley Road industrial estate, one of several new creative businesses joining the area

name: Turning Earth Ceramics Highgate - N6
description: Former indoor garden design workshop converted into a open-access ceramics studio.

name: Turning Earth Ceramics Hoxton - E2
description: Two railway arches have been repurposed into a ceramic studio.

name: Turning Earth Ceramics Leyton - E10
description: Ceramics centre for the Lee Valley, covering the entire top floor of an old hardware factory. Three rooms, providing just over 8000 sq ft of floor space; the main room is capped by its original saw-tooth glass roof feature.

name: Two-up Two-down House
description: Two-Up Two-Down House is a reworking of a Victorian mid terrace by architects Khan Bonshek. They use imaginative spatial devices to maximise the limited floor area. Double height volumes & blurring of rooms combine to create space & light.

name: UCL PEARL
description: UCL PEARL is a brand new building designed to be a laboratory that can "house the world" so that we can create different environments from around the world for experiments about people and the environment around them.
address: UCL PEARL, Yew Tree Avenue, RM10 7FN

name: UPDATED: City Information Centre
description: London's main tourist information centre is clad in a specially manufactured system of 220 pre-finished stainless steel panels. The subtly reflective surface provides a striking counterpoint to St Paul's. NOTE: Closed on Monday 19 September

name: Uncommon Projects
description: Uncommon Projects moved into their new showroom in June 2022. The showroom will be open for walk in visitors for the duration of Open House.

name: Walworth Garden
description: Our timber frame building was designed by Matrix Feminist Design Co-Operative, and built by women. It represents our community's history of activism-the same ethos that transformed our site from dereliction, into a thriving community garden

name: William Morris Society - Kelmscott House
description: Residence of Sir Francis Ronalds, George MacDonald and (from 1878-96) William Morris. Organised by William Morris Society. Access to The William Morris Society's premises in the Coach House and basement only, includes current exhibition.

name: Wimbledon Windmill
description: Rare example of a hollow post mill (1817). Grade II* listed, it now contains a museum depicting the history and development of windmills in Britain. Many working models, windmill machinery, equipment and tools.

name: Winchmore Hill Friends Meeting House & Burial Ground
description: Grade II listed, built 1790. A central double door under a bracketed cornice hood, large sash windows with delicate glazing bars. Panelled interior. Curved entrance wall allowed carriages to turn in the narrow lane. Notable burial ground.

name: Wizard Works Open Studio
description: Wizard Works, London's cutest adventure bike bag brand, will be opening their studio in North Greenwich's Design District for a behind the scenes look at all things bag making.
address: Unit 1 Building D2, 3 Dormer Yard, SE10 0EB

name: Woodfield Pavilion
description: A pre- 2nd WW - 1933 - now beautifully refurbished brick built sports pavilion surrounded by the fields of Tooting Common.
